<section class="full-height" id="climate-overview">
  <div class="bcg">
    <div class="fill-lite">
      <div class="hsContainer">
        <div class="hsContent">
          <h1>Global Change & Implications for Forests: Overview</h1>
          <p>Climate change is already here and is affecting us in far-reaching ways. Certain types of extreme weather events with links to climate change have become more frequent and/or intense, including prolonged periods of heat, heavy downpours, and, in some regions, floods and droughts. In addition warming is causing sea levels to rise and glaciers to melt. Oceans are becoming more acidic as they absorb carbon dioxide. These aspects of climate change are disrupting people's lives and damaging sectors of our economy. The following research details the effects climate change is having on our forests.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
<section class="full-height" id="climate-current">
  <div class="bcg">
    <div class="fill-lite">
      <div class="hsContainer">
        <div class="hsContent">
        <h1>Climate Change: Present</h1>
        <p>Evidence for climate change abounds and increases alongside emissions. Evidence can be found within changes of ecosystems and species distributions. These effects demonstrate the planetary warming driven by human activity.</p>
        
        <p>As summarized by the National Climate Assessment, multiple lines of independent evidence confirm that human activities are the primary cause of global warming over the past 50 years. The clearing of forests has reduced the biosphere's ability to remove carbon dioxide from the air, which, coupled with, the release of greenhouse gases from fossil fuels, has dramativally increased the concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere. CO<sub>2</sub> levels have increase by more that 40% since the Industrial Revolution.</p>
        
        <p>Other greenhouse gas emissions, such as methane and nitrous oxide emissions from agriculture add to the greenhouse gases. The pattern of temperature change in the atmosphere: warmimg near the surface, and cooling higher up in the atmosphere confirms that the buildup of greenhouse gases has caused most of the Earth's warming over the past century.</p>
        
        
        <div class="global-temp-and-co2 figure"></div>
        <p><strong>Figure 1 legend - <em>Global Temperature and Carbon Dioxide</em></strong>
        Global annual average teeperature(as measured over both land and oceans) has increased by more than 1.5&#176;F(0.8&#176;C) since 1880 (through 2012). The red bars show temperatures above the long-term average, and blue bars indicate temperatures below the long-term average. The black line shows atmospheric carbon dioxide (CO2) concentration in parts per million(ppm). (Figure source: <a href="http://nca2014.globalchange.gov/report/our-changing-climate/observed-change#tab1-images">NCA</a> updated from Karl et al. 2009<super>1</super>).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
<section class="full-height" id="climate-future">
  <div class="bcg">
    <div class="fill-lite">
      <div class="hsContainer">
        <div class="hsContent">
        <h1>Climate Change: Future</h1>
        <p>Average temperatures are projected to rise another 2&#176; to 4&#176;F in most areas of the United States over the next few decades. Reductions in some short-lived human-induced emissions that contribute to warming, such as black carbon(soot) and methane, could reduce some of the projected warming over the next couple of decades. However, the amount of warming projected beyond the next few decades is directly linked to the cumulative global emissions of heat-trapping gases and particles. By the end of this century, a roughly 3&#176;F to 5&#176;F rise is projected under a lower emissions scenario, which would require substantial reductions in emissions, vs. a 5&#176;F tp 10&#176;F rise for a higher emissions scenario assuming continued increases in emissions, predominantly from fossil fuel combustion. These projections are based on results from 16 climate models that used the two emissions scenarios in a formal inter-model comparison study. Global climate is projected to continue to change &#8212; past emissions have "committed" us to a certain amount of warming &#8212; but how much climate changes beyond that depends primarily on the amount of heat-trapping gases we choose to emit globally.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
<section class="full-height" id="climate-choice">
 <div class="bcg">
  <div class="fill-lite">
    <div class="hsContainer">
      <div class="hsContent">
        <h1>Climate Change: A Choice</h1>
        <h2>As a society we face an important decision. We have two possible climate change futures: the best case or the worst case</h2>
        <p>Global climate is projected to continue to change over this century and beyond. THe magnitude of climate change beyond the next few decades depends primarily on the amount of heat-trapping gases emitted globally, and how sensitive the Earth's climate is to those emissions.</p>
        
        <p>A certain amount of continued warming of the planet is projected to occur as a result of human-induced emissions to date; another 0.5&#176;F increase globally would be expected over the next few decades even if all emissions from human activities suddenly stopped, although natural variability could still play an important role over this time period. <em>However, choices made now and in the next few decades will determine the amount of additional future warming. Beyond mid-century, lower levels of heat-trapping gases in scenarios with reduced emissions will lead to noticeably less future warming. Higher emissions levels will result in more warming, and thus more severe impacts on human society and the natural world.</em></p>

        <p>These two scenarios &#8212; the best cases vs. the worst case &#8212; are identified by the labels rcp 2.6 vs. rcp 8.5. Climate modelers around the world have agreed on a set of four such CO<sub>2</sub> emissions scenarios. These scenarios were chosen to be representative of the emissions scenario literature &#8212; spanning a range of plausible, contrasting trajectories with respect to CO<sub>2</sub> concentrations in the atmosphere, arising from economic activity, energy sources, human population growth, and various other factors &#8212; thus their name, <b>representative concentration pathways</b>.</p>

        <p>The numbers refer to the amount of radiative forcing &#8212; extra energy retained by the atmosphere because of greenhouse gases, expressed in units of watts per square meter, relative to conditions in 1750(before the Industrial Revolution). The best-case scenario(rcp 2.6) is characterized by a "peak-then-decline" pattern, where CO<sub>2</sub> emissions rise from current-day rates of ~9 biliion tons per year, peaking around mid-21<super>st</super> century, then declining to zero by the end of the 21<super>st</super> century. The worst-case scenario(rcp 8.5) &#8212; "business as usual" &#8212; is characterized by emissions that continue to rise at a relatively high rate throughout most of the 21<super>st</super>, only stabilizing by the end of the century, at ~30 billion tons per year.</p>
        <div class="rcp-overview"></div>
        <div class="average_temp_global figure"></div>
        <p><strong>Figure 3 Legend &#8212;</strong><em>Emissions Levels Determine Temperature Rises</em>
        Different amounts of heat-trapping gases released into the atmosphere by human activities produce different projected increases in Earth's temperature. In the figure, each line represents a central estimate of global average temperature rise(relative to the 1901-1960 average) for a specific emissions pathway(rcp). Shading indicates the range(5<super>th</super> to 95<super>th</super> percentile) of results from a suite of climate models. Projections in 2099 for additional emissions pathways are indicated by the bars to the right of each panel. In all cases, temperatures are expected to rise, but the difference between lower and higher emissions pathways is substantial. The lowest emissions shown here, RCP 2.6, would result in about 2.5&#176;F of warming in this century, whereas the highest pathway, RCP 8.5 is projected to lead to more than 8&#176;F warming by 2100, with a high-end possibility of more than 11&#176;F.(Data from CMIP3, CMIP5 and NOAA NCDC). Graph and overview from <a href="http://nca2014.globalchange.gov/report/our-changing-climate/future-climate-change">NCA</a></p>
        <h2>The best case and worst case temperature projections will lead to dramatically different future worlds.</h2>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
