<section class="full-height" id="climate-mortality">
  <div class="bcg">
    <div class="fill-lite">
      <div class="hsContainer">
        <div class="hsContent">
          <h1>Increased Greenhouse Gas Emissions Lead to Continued Mortality</h1>
          <p>Recently the NCA summarized how these factors will likely influence Western U.S. forests. In short, higher temperatures and drought stress subject trees to enhanced risk of mortality, either from physiological stress fire, or by making them more prone to insect and pathogen attack.</p>
          <div class="forest-vulnerable figure"></div>
          <p><strong>Figure 7 Legend &#8212; </strong><em>Forest Vulnerability to Changing Climate</em>
          The figure shows a conceptual climate envelope analysis of forest vulnerability under current and projected future ranges of variability in climate parameters(temperature and precipitation, or drought duration and intensity). Climate models project increasing temperatures across the U.S. in coming decades, but a range of increasing or decreasing precipitation depending on region. Episodic droughts (where evaporation far exceeeds precipitation) are also expected to increase in duration and/or intensity. The overall result will be increased vulnerability of forests to periodic widespread regional mortality events resulting from trees exceeding their physiological stress thresholds.<super>1</super>(Figure source: Allen et al. 2010<super>2</super>). Graphic from <a href="http://nca2014.globalchange.gov/report/sectors/forests">NCA</a></p>
          <p>The implications are that with increased warming and increased drought, due to increased concentrations of greenhouse gases, Western forests will increasingly be at risk of enhanced mortality and reduction of the area climatically-suitable for forests. For many tree species, the most climatically-suitable areas will shift from their current locations, increasing vulnerability to insects, disease, and fire in areas that become unsuitable.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
